FBIS3-36219 "drsov023_t_94001" FBIS-SOV-94-023 Document Type:Daily Report 3 Feb 1994 BALTIC STATES Estonia Luik Speaks at Partnership for Peace Signing LD0302114094 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1100 GMT 3 Feb 94 LD0302114094 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network Language: Estonian Article Type:BFN [Text] Estonia today joined NATO's Partnership for Peace program, and as with many other eastern European countries, stated its wish to eventually become a full member of the North Atlantic bloc. Estonian Foreign Minister Juri Luik signed the partnership agreement at the NATO headquarters in Brussels. Estonia sees its possible future NATO member status as part of a wider European integration framework, Luik said at the official signing ceremony. The foreign minister noted that the Baltic countries are at the forefront in Europe in the fight for democracy and stability, and confirmed that reports coming from Moscow [as heard] cause anxiety in Estonia. Luik also stated that Estonia wants to have good relations with a democratic Russia. Only those countries who are certain of their security can be equal [word indistinct] partners for Russia, the foreign minister said. He also said that Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania form a joint partnership [words indistinct] will be used in joint NATO actions within the partnership plan.
